<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Shilha_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Numbers">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Numbers">Numbers</span></h3>
<p>In Shilha, as in most Northern Berber languages, the number system is permeated with <a href="/wiki/Arabic_grammar#Numerals" title="Arabic grammar">Arabic numbers</a>. The original cardinal numbers (one to ten) are <i>yan</i>, <i>sin</i>, <i><span class="Unicode">kraḍ</span></i>, <i><span class="Unicode">kkuẓ</span></i>, <i>smmus</i>, <i><span class="Unicode">sḍis</span></i>, <i>sa</i>, <i>ttam</i>, <i><span class="Unicode">tẓẓa</span></i>, <i>mraw</i>, but they are increasingly rare. Van den Boogert (1997) argues some of these to be of Phoenician-Punic origin. As with nouns, feminine forms are derived from the masculine: <i>yat</i> (irregular), <i>snat</i> (irregular), <i><span class="Unicode">kraṭṭ</span></i>, <i>kkuṣt</i>, <i>smmust</i>, etc. Nouns following cardinals from 1 to 10 are in the état d'annexion. Above ten, they are not pluralized and <i>n</i> 'of' precedes the noun: contrast <i><span class="Unicode">kkuẓ wu-ssan</span></i> (four <small>EA</small>-day.pl) 'four days' with <i><span class="Unicode">kraḍ d mraw n wuššn</span></i> (three and ten of <small>EA</small>-jackal) 'thirteen jackals'. In the tens, Arabic numerals are used, e.g. <i>ɛšrin</i> 'twenty', <i>tltin</i> 'thirty', etc. Tens are combined with Arabic units. Sometimes cardinals behave like nouns in that they are countable as well: <i><span class="Unicode">sin id-ɛšrin n tgʷmma</span></i> (two pl-twenty of <small>EA</small>-houses) 'forty houses'. Ordinal numbers are constructed by use of <i>wiss</i> (m) or <i>tiss</i> plus the cardinal number, e.g. <i><span class="Unicode">wiss kraḍ</span></i> 'the third (m)'.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Shilha_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Vocabulary">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Vocabulary">Vocabulary</span></h2>
<p>Like all Berber languages, Shilha has absorbed quite some Arabic vocabulary, especially in the religious domain.</p>
<table class="metadata plainlinks ambox mbox-small-left ambox-notice" style="">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image"><a href="/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg" class="image"><img alt="Wiki letter w cropped.svg" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/20px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png" width="20" height="14" /></a></td>
<td class="mbox-text" style="">This section requires <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Shilha_language&amp;action=edit" class="external text" rel="nofollow">expansion</a>.</td>
