<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b> Note that early Arab geographers used the name <i>chleuh</i> to refer to the whole of Morocco, see <a href="#CITEREFBoogert1997">Boogert (1997</a>:1)</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b> Tashdiid may occur with sukun in Shilha, which never occurs in Arabic.</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b> Vowel length isn't distinctive in Shilha but orthographically long vowels may indicate <a href="/wiki/Prosody_(linguistics)" title="Prosody (linguistics)">prosody</a>, see <a href="#CITEREFBoogert1997">Boogert (1997</a>:66)</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b> Note that this usage is the mirror-image of Maghrebi.</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20">^</a></b> Syllable-final /ə/ demonstrates its phonemicity, e.g. /jəwət/.</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21">^</a></b> This word has no attested cognates in Berber languages</li>
